Good hunting &amp; May Innoruuk guide you to truth. <p><img src="http://noirdaila.homestead.com/files/NaenSign.JPG"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=valquisssilverpalm>Valquiss Silverpalm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 188<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/25/02 8:59:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1162.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Recruiting</span><hr size=1> Ah. In light of the clarification, I have some new advise to give.<br>
<br>
First, don't be in a hurry to add people.  You probably shouldn't need to knock down anyone's door to add people to your guild, and if you need to there are problems that run deeper than recruiting procedures.  Let expansion happen naturally.  I'll clarify what I mean by that right now.<br>
<br>
Second, let everyone in your guild know you are actively looking to expand.  Make a Motd to that effect if you want.  The command is /guildmotd (text here) .  Tell your whole guild to be on the look out for good, unguilded companions.  Meeting someone through grouping is the absolute best way to get a solid read on their character.<br>
<br>
Third, wait to either meet someone yourself or have someone recommended to you by another guild mate.  Then make opportunities to group with them.  Or if you can't, recommend that others in their level range do.  Then find out what they thought.  If you hear good things, chances are the person will fit in your guild.<br>
<br>
This may sound a bit complicated, but really it's a whole lot easier if you have a discussion board your guild regularly visits.  Then you have an application area where each person who is under consideration has a thread, and guildmembers who know anything about them can post replies.  That's roughly what Starspun does.  We don't have a voting system, but all guildmembers have a chance to voice their opinions (if they have opinions and anything to base them on) and eventually enough opinions collect that an officer makes the call.<br>
<br>
All that having been said, I still think (as I have stated elsewhere) that the best way to recruit for a guild is to make the application process dependent on the energy and enthusiasm of the applicant, not the other way around.  If someone cares enough to seek out the guild, make a formal application to join, go out of his or her way to meet other members of the guild and group with them etc., then chances are very strong they will make a solid addition to the guild.  If they have to be sought after, chased down, and convinced to join in guild activities, then chances are they will make poor guildmates at best.<br>
<br>
One final thought and piece of advise.  If you are looking to build and add a few people fast, try to make sure there are concentrations of your guild in various places.  Groups of three or four if possible, just hunting and doing whatever it is your guild does.  Invite other people to join as convenient.  That way a few members of your guild can meet them all at once.  A few quick votes in their favor might result.  That's still a bit faster and easier than I like, but it will help you build.<br>
<br>
